Prompt writing is like trying to guide a morning calving event with precise muscular control. You can apply discipline at the point of release, but that control sits downstream. Upstream factors - diet, hydration, and physiology - have already shaped what arrives.

When those upstream conditions dominate, they don’t get overridden; they pass through. The output reflects prior inputs more than last-moment control.

In the same way, prompt constraints operate at the surface, while training distribution, reward bias, and token frequency act upstream. Strong biases continue to appear because they remain the lowest-effort path for the model to complete its task.

So the craft isn’t about forcing control at the end. It’s about shaping what flows into that moment in the first place.

GIGO
